    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Common air-breathing isopod related to terrestrial woodlice and found just above the drift line on rocky shores. Body broadly oval, flattened and dorsally smooth. Colour dark brown with fine white lines.&nbsp; Head with distinctive spade-like projection between the antennae (after which species in named); antennae only about half of length of thorax. Abdomen short with separate broad segments. Uropods short, each with single club–shaped ramus.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_505",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 16 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_506",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Restricted to Southwestern Cape, between about Saldanha and Cape Agulhas.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_507",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Until recently rarely reported, but now known to be common around and above the drift line of rocky shores in the SW Cape where drift kelp is cast ashore. May co-occur in mixed populations with both the horned isopod <i>Deto echinata</i> and with the sea slater <i>L. glabrata,</i> but tends to extend higher on the shore that either of those species. Feeds on drift kelp and other algae, and may also scavenge on dead animals. Most active at night.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_508",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Mainly kelp but also other drift algae and organic debris.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_509",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all isopods the eggs are retained within a marsupial pouch between the walking legs of females and hatch into fully developed juveniles.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_510",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Often in mixed populations with <i>Deto echinata</i>, but that species is easily recognised by the unusual dorsal ‘horns’ on each thoracic segment. Also found together with <i>Ligia </i>species, but these have a narrower body and elongate, branched uropods.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_511",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 88).<br><br>Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isopods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 160).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_512",
